  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Africa Regional (Mozambique, Tanzania, and Zambia): Building Enabling Legal Frameworks for Sustainable Land Use and Low-Carbon Investment</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="2">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">1. To develop an innovative comparative legal assessment methodology and frameworks that improve the knowledge base on how laws, institutions and regulatory frameworks affect land use change and low-carbon investment in Sub-Saharan Africa. 2. To analyze how social and environmental safeguards have been integrated and implemented in regulations across key sectors that are affecting land use change. 3.To develop an initial set of legal and institutional reform proposals that encourage implementation of strategies for sustainable land use and low-carbon investment in the three target countries.</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="3">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Governments of Mozambique, Tanzania and Zambia, investors in low-carbon projects. Poor and vulnerable groups, particularly rural communities.</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">The project aimed to assess the implementation of social and environmental safeguards in existing regulations of Mozambique, Tanzania and Zambia, and develop recommendations for legal and institutional reform in key sectors affecting REDD+ and other low-carbon investment, and land use change.</narrative>
  </description>
